### CMake support for SWIR Python package ###

One of the pending issues on my task list has been the integration of the SWIR Python package with the rest of the code, connecting everything through the [CMake](http://www.cmake.org) configuration environment. Though [Python](http://python.org) comes with its own configuration and build tools -- as well as testing frameworks -- we definitely want to have all the parts integrated into a single package. The obstacle for quite a while however was that we were lacking agreement on how to organize the directory structure of the source code; as it is with software developers from different background, there may be diverging views on how to lay out the individual sub-parts of the software -- this took a while to settle, but as begin of this week this has been resolved. However last Monday we finally managed to resolve the issue and agree on a directory layout:

    swir
    |-- config                          ...  Extension modules for configuration scripts
    |-- docs                            ...  API and general documentation
    |   |-- doxygen
    |   `-- sphinx
    `-- source
        |-- c                           ...  Library and tools written in C
        |   |-- swir
        |   |-- tests
        |   `-- tools
        `-- python                      ...  SWIR Python package
            |-- build
            |-- scripts
            |-- swir
            `-- tests

With this out of the way, the first thing I did was to migrate the C sources into the structure: since all the configruation scripts already were in a shape, that the top-level entry point rather easily could be moved, the migration could be completed over lunch-time and well before the progress meeting scheduled later the same day. The Python code moved into its new location two days later, leaving me with the task to connect it with the rest of the CMake infrastructure; as there is actually very little to build, what the CMake configuration script essentially provides is a wrapper around the Python setup tools:

    add_custom_target (PythonBuild
        COMMAND ${PYTHON_EXECUTABLE} ${PYTHON_SETUP_PY} build
        DEPENDS ${PYTHON_SETUP_PY}
        WORKING_DIRECTORY ${CMAKE_CURRENT_SOURCE_DIR}
        COMMENT "Build Python source code..."
    )

Alongside the build instructions for the package -- which in a follow-up step then can be installed into the system -- also testing should be handled: while (once more) Python comes with its own set of tools, in the end everything should be channeled through _CTest_, in order to send a complete summary to the CDash server, where results can be inspected and tracked. Wrapping this bit is rather straight-forward as well: the only extra bit in here is to prepend all Python tests with a `pytest` instead of the usual `test`, which then allows for the usage of regular expressions when trying to run tests selectively.

    ## Scan 'test' sub-directory for scripts contained therein
    file (GLOB PythonTests tests/*.py)

    foreach (_testSource ${PythonTests})

        ## Extract name of test, splitting off file extension
        get_filename_component(_testName ${_testSource} NAME_WE)
        ## Define test
        add_test (py${_testName} ${PYTHON_EXECUTABLE} -m doctest ${_testSource})
        ## Test properties: define PYTHONPATH to import package
        set_tests_properties(py${_testName}
            PROPERTIES
            ENVIRONMENT "PYTHONPATH=${CMAKE_CURRENT_SOURCE_DIR}"
            )

    endforeach (_testSource)

One of the immediate outcomes of the above integration steps was, that as with the C library, the Python package comes with a number of external dependencies, which need to be resolved in order to run succesfully. One of the first problems I ran into after integration of the tests, was that essetially all of them would fail; since I'd trust that Evert would not have checked the code if there was something fundamentally wrong with it, I had to assume there was something in the system configuration which was not ready yet for working with the Python package (and its tests).

